PROMPT chinese_script_evolution
WITH BUDGET 8000 tokens
USING MODEL "claude-sonnet-4-5"

SELECT
    system_role("You are a Chinese paleography and historical linguistics expert specializing in the evolutionary development of Chinese writing systems from ancient oracle bones through modern characters, with deep knowledge of character form changes, historical contexts, and the socio-political factors driving script transitions.")

GENERATE
    explain_script_evolution("Explain the evolution from oracle bone script → bronze script → seal script → clerical script → regular script. Cover: 1) Oracle bone script (甲骨文 jiǎgǔwén) as the earliest known Chinese writing system from the Shang dynasty (c. 1250-1046 BCE), characterized by pictographic representations carved on turtle shells and ox scapulae for divination, with highly variable character forms and direct pictorial connections to represented objects, 2) Bronze script (金文 jīnwén) emerging during late Shang and flourishing in Western Zhou dynasty (c. 1046-771 BCE), showing evolution from oracle bone forms with more standardized and decorative character shapes cast or engraved on ritual bronze vessels, demonstrating increased complexity and artistic elaboration while maintaining pictographic elements, 3) Seal script (篆書 zhuànshū) development during Eastern Zhou and standardization under Qin Shi Huang (221-206 BCE), representing the first major systematization of Chinese writing with uniform character forms, regulated stroke patterns, and the elimination of regional variants, establishing the foundation for all subsequent Chinese scripts, 4) Clerical script (隸書 lìshū) emergence during Qin dynasty and dominance in Han dynasty (206 BCE - 220 CE) as a practical administrative writing system, featuring simplified strokes, horizontal emphasis, and the transformation from curved seal script lines to angular geometric forms, making writing faster and more suitable for bureaucratic documentation, 5) Regular script (楷書 kǎishū) development from late Han through Tang dynasty (618-907 CE) as the standardized form still used today, characterized by clear stroke separation, balanced proportions, and systematic stroke order rules, representing the culmination of Chinese character evolution into a mature writing system, 6) Chronological timeline showing approximate dates and overlapping periods of use for each script type, 7) Driving factors behind each transition including technological changes (writing materials and tools), political needs (standardization for administration), social changes (literacy expansion), and aesthetic preferences, 8) Specific examples of the same character written in each script stage to illustrate the evolutionary progression and transformation patterns, 9) How each script reflects its historical context and practical requirements, from divination records to imperial administration to literary expression, 10) The technical aspects of how character structure became increasingly systematic and rule-based through each evolutionary stage, 11) Regional variations and the role of political unification in script standardization, 12) The lasting impact of this evolutionary sequence on modern Chinese writing and the continuous thread connecting ancient oracle bones to contemporary Chinese characters.")
WITH OUTPUT BUDGET 4000 tokens, TEMPERATURE 0.1, FORMAT markdown;